        <TD style="width: 95%;">
          <BIG><BIG style=
          "color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">RFO-BASIC!</BIG></BIG><BR>
          <BR>
          <SPAN style="font-family: monospace;">An opensource BASIC
          program</SPAN> <SPAN style=
          "font-family: monospace;">interpreter</SPAN> <SPAN style=
          "font-family: monospace;">for
          ANDROID.</SPAN><SMALL>&nbsp; ( by <A href=
          "http://laughton.com/basic/">Paul
          Laughton</A>.)<BR></SMALL><BR>
          <BIG style="font-style: italic;"><SPAN style=
          "color: rgb(51, 51, 255);"><SPAN style=
          "color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">The FASTEST way to <SPAN style=
          "color: black;">make an Android APP !!!</SPAN> (</SPAN>do
          you want to <SPAN style=
          "color: rgb(0, 0, 153); text-decoration: underline;">program</SPAN>
          without the mess of java, xml and slow emulators? -
          <SPAN style="color: black;">read
          on..</SPAN>)</SPAN></BIG><BR>
          <BR>
          Features :&nbsp;<BR>

          <TABLE>
            <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD style=
                "vertical-align: top; width: 100px; background-color: rgb(103, 103, 103);">
                <BR></TD>

                <TD style=
                "vertical-align: top; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">Quick
                Development</TD>

                <TD style=
                "vertical-align: top; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">
                Interfaces<BR></TD>

                <TD style=
                "vertical-align: top; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">
                Android Phone Resources</TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style=
                "vertical-align: top; background-color: rgb(103, 103, 103);">
                <IMG style="width: 128px; height: 128px;" alt=""
                src="pics/logo.png"><BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top; width: 25%;" class=
                "c64">Interpreter runs *.bas files<BR>
                <BR>
                No compilation !<BR>
                No Java !<BR>
                No XML !<BR>
                Easy APK building!<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><SMALL>Graphics /
                Console<BR>
                HTML (browser / data)<BR>
                File I/O<BR>
                SQL database<BR>
                shell / root shell<BR>
                TCP/IP sockets<BR>
                FTP<BR>
                <BR></SMALL></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><SMALL>GPS,<BR>
                Device Sensors (acc, temp, motion..etc)<BR>
                Audio play/record, tone generation,<BR>
                Camera,<BR>
                Bluetooth,<BR>
                Email, SMS.<BR></SMALL> <SMALL>Text To
                Speech</SMALL><BR></TD>
              </TR>
            </TBODY>
          </TABLE><BR>
          <HR style="width: 100%; height: 2px;">
          <SPAN style=
          "text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">Writing</SPAN><BR>


          <DIV style="margin-left: 40px;">
            Edit programs with the built-in editor ( inside&nbsp;
            BASIC! interpreter app)<BR>
            <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">OR</SPAN><BR>
            Any desktop editor and then copy *.bas file/s to the
            Android phone for the interpreter app.<BR>
          </DIV><BR>
          <SPAN style=
          "color: rgb(0, 0, 153); text-decoration: underline;">Testing</SPAN><BR>


          <DIV style="margin-left: 40px;">
            Because the language is interpreted, there is
            <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">no waiting</SPAN>
            for compilation or building process during
            development.<BR>
            Because the execution is on the phone, there is no need
            for a slow emulator. What you see is 'really' what you
            get.<BR>
          </DIV><BR>
          <SPAN style=
          "text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">Deploying</SPAN><BR>


          <DIV style="margin-left: 40px;">
            When the program is finished, you have the option to
            distribute as .bas files and run on an Android phone
            (previously installed with interpreter),<BR>
            <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">OR</SPAN><BR>
            Wrapped with a copy of the interpreter and <SPAN style=
            "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">packaged as an .APK</SPAN>
            ready to be installed onto any Android phone and run as
            a standalone app.<BR>
          </DIV><SPAN style=
          "text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"><BR></SPAN>
          The Interpreter is found on <A href=
          "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.rfo.basic&amp;hl=en">
          Google Play Store</A> is called&nbsp; BASIC!<BR>
          <BR>
          For serious programming, it is easier to edit on a PC and
          then transfer the files to phone for running/testing.
          There are some tools to streamline this.<BR>
          <HR style="width: 100%; height: 2px;">
          <BR>
          <SPAN style=
          "text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">Development
          Tools</SPAN><BR>

          <TABLE>
            <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top; width: 100px;">
                Transfer<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top; width: 30%;">
                <A href="http://mougino.free.fr/">RFO-BASIC!
                Launcher</A><BR>
                <SMALL>(windows)<BR>
                <BR>
                versions for SciTE or Notepad++<BR>
                <BR></SMALL></TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">Enables an editor on a PC to
                send a BASIC! program file to the phone and to run
                it with the interpreter.<BR>
                <BR>
                <A href=
                "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.rfo.basic&amp;hl=en">
                BASIC!</A> interpreter must already be
                installed<BR>
                <A href=
                "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.rfo.BASICLauncher">
                BASIC! Launcher (WiFi)</A> (receiver) must be
                installed on the phone.<BR>
                <A href="http://mougino.free.fr/">PC Launcher</A>
                (sender) is called with the chosen editor.<BR>
                <BR></TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Transfer<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">
                  <DIV style="text-align: left;">
                    &nbsp; <SPAN style=
                    "text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">
                    *&nbsp; The Manual Method&nbsp;&nbsp;
                    *</SPAN><BR>
                  </DIV><SMALL>(linux, windows)<BR>
                  <BR>
                  This is the most convenient method as having a
                  mapped SMB drive means you can treat the shared
                  drive on your phone like any other
                  drive.<BR></SMALL>
                </TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">
                  <SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(102, 51, 102);"><SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(56, 28, 56);">An alternative to the
                  launcher is to just copy the .bas file to your
                  android phone and send it to the BASIC!
                  interpreter.<BR></SPAN></SPAN> <SMALL>(this is
                  all the launcher does
                  anyway).</SMALL><SPAN style="color: rgb(102, 51, 102);"><SPAN style="color: rgb(56, 28, 56);"><BR>

                  <BR></SPAN></SPAN> 1. First install <A href=
                  "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.funkyfresh.samba&amp;hl=en">
                  Samba Filesharing</A> on your phone which will
                  <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">share your
                  phone's drive</SPAN> via wi-fi.<BR>
                  You will need a rooted phone, if you are not
                  rooted, then use the <A href="#ftp">ftp
                  method</A>.<BR>
                  <BR>
                  2. Then, on your PC, find and <A href=
                  "../linux/lubuntu-samba.html#android_host">map</A>
                  the shared drive.<BR style=
                  "color: rgb(0, 102, 0);">
                  <BR style="color: rgb(0, 102, 0);">
                  3. <SPAN style="color: rgb(0, 102, 0);">Use a
                  batch file to <SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">copy the .bas file to
                  the phone</SPAN>.<BR>
                  e.g<BR></SPAN>

                  <DIV>
                    <SMALL>linux : cp myfile.bas &nbsp;
                    /mnt/sda1/rfo-basic/source/try.bas<SMALL><BR></SMALL></SMALL>
                  </DIV><SMALL>or<BR></SMALL>

                  <DIV>
                    <SMALL>windows : copy myfile.bas &nbsp;
                    G:\rfo-basic\source\try.bas</SMALL><BR>
                  </DIV><BR>
                  Use a fixed name on the phone, eg. "<SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">try.bas</SPAN>".<SPAN style="color: rgb(102, 0, 0);"><BR>
                  </SPAN><BR>
                  <SMALL>(<SPAN style="font-style: italic;">Some
                  editors allow Fkey commands to copy</SPAN>
                  <SPAN style="color: black;"><SPAN style=
                  "font-style: italic;">the current file to your
                  phone, e.g geany, scite, context..etc.</SPAN>
                  )</SPAN></SMALL><BR>
                  <SPAN style="color: rgb(102, 0, 0);"><BR style=
                  "color: rgb(102, 0, 0);"></SPAN> 4. <A href=
                  "hew/first.html#shortcut"><SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">Create a Launcher
                  shortcut</SPAN></A> on the Android desktop
                  (BASIC! interpreter, with <SPAN style=
                  "color: rgb(0, 0, 153);">try.bas</SPAN> as the
                  input program filename. <SMALL>(you only need to
                  do this once)</SMALL><BR style="color: white;">
                  <BR>
                  Now you can run the program anytime by just
                  pressing the shortcut !<BR>
                  <BR>
                </TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Transfer</TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><A name="ftp" id=
                "ftp"></A>FTP<BR>
                <BR>
                <SMALL>For most, this would be the most
                conventional method as there are many ftp clients
                and servers already out there.</SMALL><BR></TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">Similar to the manual method
                is to<BR>
                Install an <A href=
                "https://sites.google.com/site/andreasliebigapps/ftpserver">
                <SPAN style="text-decoration: underline;">FTP
                server</SPAN></A> on you phone <SMALL>(no need for
                root)</SMALL>.<BR>
                And an <A href=
                "https://filezilla-project.org/download.php?type=client">
                <SPAN style="text-decoration: underline;">FTP
                client</SPAN></A> on your PC.<BR>
                <BR>
                Make sure your main prorgram matches the name in
                the shortcut on the phone <SMALL>(see manual method
                above)</SMALL>.<BR></TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Building<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><A href=
                "http://api.viglink.com/api/click?format=go&amp;jsonp=vglnk_jsonp_13983327695246&amp;key=354d60520f2c76c930c5c04f9ab39ae3&amp;libId=1857c3e6-33c4-4112-b8b7-bf59c166a01e&amp;loc=http%3A%2F%2Frfobasic.freeforums.org%2Fquick-apk-version-v01-79-00-released-t2371.html&amp;v=1&amp;out=http%3A%2F%2Fmougino.free.fr%2Fquickapk.html&amp;ref=http%3A%2F%2Frfobasic.freeforums.org%2Fannouncements-f21.html&amp;title=rfobasic.freeforums.org%20-%20View%20topic%20-%20Quick%20APK%20version%20v01.79.00%20released&amp;txt=http%3A%2F%2Fmougino.free.fr%2Fquickapk.html">
                QuickAPK</A><BR>
                <SMALL>(windows)</SMALL><BR></TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">Quick APK is an all-in-one
                solution which bundles together the basic program,
                resources and the interpreter.<BR>
                Requires: <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">JRE</SPAN><BR></TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Building<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><A href=
                "http://stefanopalmeri.altervista.org/xab/">XAB&nbsp;&nbsp;
                x-apk-builder</A><BR>
                <SMALL>(linux)</SMALL><BR></TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">XAB uses Gambas as a front
                end to a scripted builder for linux.<BR>
                Requires: <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">gambas</SPAN>,
                <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">sdk,
                ant</SPAN> and <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">java/jdk</SPAN>. (<A href=
                "misc/xab/xab.html">installation
                guide</A>)<BR></TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;"><A href=
                "http://stefanopalmeri.altervista.org/xqa/">XQA
                &nbsp; x-quick-apk builder</A><BR>
                <SMALL>(linux)</SMALL><BR></TD>

                <TD class="cell_underline" style=
                "vertical-align: top;">XQA is the same as XAB
                except it does away sdk and ant.<BR>
                Requires: <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">gambas</SPAN>, and
                <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">java/jdk</SPAN>.
                <SMALL>(see xab installation
                guide).</SMALL><BR></TD>
              </TR>

              <TR>
                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Building<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">Manual
                Building<BR></TD>

                <TD style="vertical-align: top;">The lowest level
                of building is to use <SPAN style=
                "color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">Eclipse</SPAN> with
                Android's <SPAN style="color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">SDK
                and java/jdk.</SPAN><BR>
                Instructions for building this way is found in the
                <A href=
                "http://laughton.com/basic/help/De_Re_BASIC%21.htm">
                BASIC! Manual</A>.<BR></TD>
              </TR>
            </TBODY>
          </TABLE><BR>
